USA TODAYThirty-two people were sickened in an E. coli outbreak linked to romaine lettuce in 11 states.
(Photo: Getty Images)WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. – Food-safety investigators have traced the romaine lettuce E. coli outbreak to Californian growing fields, but regulators still say it's unsafe to eat the leafy green in 11 states.
Dr. Robert R. Redfield, director of the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, recently updated Americans about the romaine lettuce outbreak.
"There are no exceptions – all romaine lettuce must be discarded, regardless of brand, type or if it is in a mixture."
Nov. 23: Romaine lettuce linked to E. coli scare likely came from California: FDA commissionerNov. 23: President Trump's Thanksgiving meal included Caesar salad amid romaine E. coli outbreakFood and Drug Administration Commissioner Scott Gottlieb said Friday morning that the outbreak is linked to California-based romaine lettuce.